FreeBSD 13.1-p amd64.
On some Core 2 Duo and "same" Xeons I found very low temperature.
For example 13°C on CPU cores in server room with 16°C air temperature, or 33°C on desktop with 28°C in room. In same server room Core 2 Quad, Core i7 920/930, Xeon X3430, Xeon 3104 have temperature from 24 to 50.
I started explore.

dev.cpu.X.temperature = dev.cpu.X.coretemp.tjmax - dev.cpu.X.coretemp.delta
For other Core 2 Quad Q6600 tjmax = 100, but for Core 2 Duo 85 - weird…

Check sources: https://cgit.freebsd.org/src/tree/sys/dev/coretemp/coretemp.c
	if ((cpu_model == 0xf && cpu_stepping >= 2) || cpu_model == 0xe) {
		/*
		 * On some Core 2 CPUs, there's an undocumented MSR that
		 * can tell us if Tj(max) is 100 or 85.
		 *
		 * The if-clause for CPUs having the MSR_IA32_EXT_CONFIG was adapted
		 * from the Linux coretemp driver.
		 */
		msr = rdmsr(MSR_IA32_EXT_CONFIG);
		if (msr & (1 << 30))
			sc->sc_tjmax = 85;
        } else if (cpu_model == 0x17) {

Open linux driver: https://git.kernel.org/pub/scm/linux/kernel/git/torvalds/linux.git/tree/drivers/hwmon/coretemp.c
		/*
		 * Now we can detect the mobile CPU using Intel provided table
		 * http://softwarecommunity.intel.com/Wiki/Mobility/720.htm
		 * For Core2 cores, check MSR 0x17, bit 28 1 = Mobile CPU
		 */
		err = rdmsr_safe_on_cpu(id, 0x17, &eax, &edx);
		if (err) {
			dev_warn(dev,
				 "Unable to access MSR 0x17, assuming desktop"
				 " CPU\n");
			usemsr_ee = 0;
